{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"[PASS 1 — G6 Approach soundness, anti-patterns & alternative-selection]\n\nAFFIRMATIONS (G6 criteria this plan satisfies):\n- Mechanism correctness (core): the resolve-ref→immutable-SHA → faithful `git read-tree`+`checkout-index` materialization → content-addressed `<cache>/<sha>/` cache → delete-on-last-close reader safety → flock GC interlock chain is logically complete and explicitly handles the concurrent/failure/edge cases (single-flight collapse, ENOENT→re-materialize self-heal, atomic dir-rename all-or-nothing population, crash leaves only tmp/ swept on startup, no-PID-lease liveness). The TOCTOU surface is named and closed where it matters (S2b AC4 byte-total under concurrent populate-vs-evict; S4 AC3 compare-and-set pin serialized through the event-append boundary).\n- Fitness-for-purpose (signing): the manifest-channel SHA binding is verified against real source — `signing._canonical_payload` signs `{v, algorithm, ticket_id, manifest}` and `compute_signature` signs the full `manifest: list[str]`, so a `verified-at-sha:<sha>` manifest STEP enters the signed bytes without a `PAYLOAD_VERSION` bump or prior-signature invalidation. The \"bind WHAT code was verified\" goal is genuinely solved, not proxied.\n- Positive rationale present: the plan states WHY for each non-obvious choice — faithful read-tree+checkout-index over lossy `git archive` (export-ignore/export-subst/LFS/submodule fidelity), manifest-channel over payload-schema bump (no signature invalidation), delete-on-last-close over the rejected PID+heartbeat lease — each grounded in named prior art (Gitaly, Sourcegraph gitserver/zoekt, Bazel, ccache, Nix, in-toto). The ADR captures the cross-cutting decisions. This satisfies the G6 positive-rationale requirement.\n- Approach selection: I generated two structurally-different alternatives — (a) `git worktree add` per ref, and (b) a bare mirror clone with per-ref `GIT_DIR` object-DB reads — and judge the chosen approach defensibly at-least-as-good: worktrees take repo-level index/config locks (the exact contention parent AC4 sets out to eliminate) and still need a checkout to yield a faithful tree; the content-addressed snapshot is more testable (immutable SHA = perfect cache key, no staleness) and lower blast-radius (object DB untouched, reads off a copied tree). No clearly-superior alternative was missed. PASS — alternatives discarded, not written into the plan.\n\nFINDING (G6 — fitness-for-purpose / hidden data-flow gap: the plan-review claim-gate path still hashes the MUTABLE working tree, so the named goal \"never the server's mutable checkout\" is unmet for that one gate)\n- criteria: G6 (1) mechanism correctness — hidden data-flow incompleteness; G6 (2) solves the named problem, not a proxy.\n- location: parent AC1 (\"No code-reading gate reads the server's working tree in attested mode\") + AC2 (reproducible against the pinned SHA); S4b `piney-gold-day` (e308) AC1/AC2 + file_impact (signing.py); S3 `pale-peer-hawk` (fa49) Scope/file_impact; src/rebar/llm/plan_review/attest.py.\n- evidence:\n  1. THREE sign/verify-side hashing sites in attest.py all root on the MUTABLE checkout via `_config.repo_root`, not on a snapshot dir: `dependency_hashes()` (attest.py:106-107, docstring line 92 \"hashed from the working tree\"), `_rehash()` (attest.py:191-196, \"Re-hash ... at CURRENT working-tree content\"), and the ADR-0002 claim-gate freshness re-check (attest.py:325-326), with the unscoped whole-HEAD fallback at attest.py:338 also resolving through `_config.repo_root`.\n  2. S4b (e308) consolidates these into \"ONE shared ref-resolution boundary\" in signing.py (its AC1, file_impact src/rebar/signing.py) — but its What/AC describe collapsing TWO resolution SITES into one; nothing states that the shared boundary hashes from the PINNED-SHA SNAPSHOT DIR rather than from the working tree. Consolidating two mutable-tree hash sites into one mutable-tree boundary still hashes the mutable tree.\n  3. S3 (fa49) re-roots only \"the gate's file tools (pai_tools root / cfg.repo_path)\"; its file_impact is completion.py/pai_tools.py/mcp_server.py — NOT attest.py. So the snapshot re-rooting that satisfies AC1 for the LLM gates never reaches the plan-review attestation hashing path.\n  4. No child's file_impact lists attest.py; the snapshot-handle→hashing-path data-flow is described by no ticket.\n- why this is a G6 (not merely G4) concern: independent of WHO owns the seam, the mechanism as decomposed does not achieve the parent's stated goal for the plan-review/claim-gate gate — an attested plan-review would sign `file_impact` hashes and the claim-gate would re-hash, both off whatever branch/dirty state the shared checkout happens to be in. That re-introduces exactly the moving-checkout false-verdict the epic exists to kill (the motivating session bug), so the solution as written is a proxy for the named problem on this path, not a fix.\n- checklist_item: - [ ] State, in S4b (e308) and/or S3, that the shared ref-resolution boundary hashes `file_impact`/freshness-re-check paths from the PINNED-SHA SNAPSHOT (the materialized tree), not from `_config.repo_root` — so attest.py's dependency_hashes()/_rehash()/ADR-0002 re-check read the snapshot, satisfying parent AC1's \"never the server's working tree\" for the plan-review gate; add attest.py to the owning child's file_impact and a covering AC.\n- suggested_fix: In S4b's \"What\", change \"ONE shared ref-resolution boundary\" to specify that the boundary resolves the client ref to the pinned SHA AND hashes paths from the snapshot dir materialized at that SHA (the S1 handle), replacing `_config.repo_root` as the hash base in dependency_hashes() (attest.py:106-107), _rehash() (attest.py:191-196), and the freshness re-check (attest.py:325-326); list src/rebar/llm/plan_review/attest.py in S4b's file_impact and add an AC (\"the shared boundary hashes from the pinned-SHA snapshot, not the working tree\"). The existing S4b negative test (its AC2, \"both gates hash at the SAME ref\") should additionally assert that ref is the pinned SHA's snapshot content, not the current checkout."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782531403470015001,"uuid":"2267e595-0dfe-401e-a6a1-fdf59b2fddcc"}